data.content:
Use EF Core 7+ **bulk operations** — `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync`. They translate directly to SQL, bypassing the change tracker entirely:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk UPDATE — single SQL statement, zero entities loaded
var cutoffDate = DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6);
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < cutoffDate)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk DELETE — single SQL statement, zero entities loaded
var logCutoff = DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1);
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Key differences from your original code:**

| | Original | `ExecuteUpdate/Delete` |
|---|---|---|
| SQL round-trips | SELECT + many UPDATEs/DELETEs | 1 statement each |
| Memory | All matching entities loaded | Zero entities loaded |
| Change tracker | Involved | Bypassed |
| Speed (500K/2M rows) | Minutes | Seconds |

**Caveats:**
- These **bypass the change tracker** — any already-tracked entities won't reflect the changes. Call `_db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` afterward if needed.
- No EF `SaveChanges` interceptors or soft-delete filters will fire — the SQL runs directly.
- If the delete is massive (2M rows), consider batching to avoid long-held locks:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < logCutoff)
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
